                        Conference Information

Location:
The 10th Annual Symposium on Computational Geometry will be held
on the campus of the State University of New York, Stony Brook,
located on the north shore of Long Island approximately
sixty miles from Manhattan.  The talks will take place in the Student
Union building.

Accommodations:
Danfords Inn is the official conference hotel,
and has elegant accommodations with views overlooking Port Jefferson Harbor.
Port Jefferson, an old ship building port settled in the 17th century, is
a popular tourist destination with shops, restaurants, and theater.
Danfords Inn was rated second nationwide for a suburban hotel
by Lodging and Hospitality magazine in 1993.

The conference room rate is substantially reduced from Danfords regular
in-season rate.
Be sure to say that you are with the ``Geometry'' conference to get the
discount rate.
A nice daily breakfast buffet and ground transportation to/from
Islip/MacArthur Airport (with advance reservation) are included, making
this a better value.

The welcoming reception and business meeting will be held at Danfords.
Bus transportation will be provided daily for the short trip to the talks at
Stony Brook.

For graduate students and those on a budget, dormitory rooms are available
in Kelly Quad on the Stony Brook campus.
They are arranged in suites of three rooms with two beds per room,
including a sitting room and a bathroom.
Be aware that these accommodations are very spartan, without air
conditioning, TV, outside phones, and maid service.
The dorms are within walking distance of the talks, and bus transportation
will be provided for the short trips to the welcoming reception and business
meeting at Danfords.

One final option is the Holiday Inn Express in Centereach (516-471-8000),
priced between Danfords and the dorm.
It has nice accommodations but is removed enough from the
centers of activity that you should plan to have a car.
%It is very suitable for families but we warn
%you will be utterly miserable here unless you have a car.

Banquet:
The buffet-style banquet will be held at The Carriage House of the Museums
of Stony Brook, which displays an internationally acclaimed collection
of 250 horse-drawn vehicles.  Other buildings at the Museums host a variety
of collections, including the paintings of William Sidney Mount.
Our caterer is technically-trained -- with a B.S. in Computer Science
from Stony Brook -- and so is well-equipped to deal with our special needs.

Transportation:
For flyers, we recommend the Islip/MacArthur airport, which is served by
several airlines including American, USAir, United, and Delta.
It is closest to Stony Brook, and Danfords Inn provides free limo service
with one week's advance reservation.  International travelers should fly
into New York JFK or LaGuardia airport.  Expect to spend at least an hour
reaching Stony Brook from JFK or LaGuardia, possibly much longer due
to traffic delays.

Airport limos will provide door-to-door service, but should be
reserved in advance.  (The limo driver will need your flight info,
etc, in order to arrange to meet you at the airport.)  Companies
include Spartan Limo ((516) 928-5454; prices are $28 to $32 from JFK
or LaGuardia, $18 to $22 to/from Islip; they accept cash or check),
Winston ((800) 424-7767; prices are $36 from JFK or LaGuardia, $20
from Islip; they accept cash, credit cards, and NY state checks), and
Classic ((516) 567-5100, (800) 666-4949 (out-of-state); prices are
$36 from JFK or LaGuardia, $20 from Islip; they accept cash and
credit cards).  Limos offer substantial discounts for groups of 2 or
more.

Stony Brook can be reached from Penn Station, New York City, via the
Long Island Railroad (LIRR).  Make sure you are on ``The Port
Jefferson Line''.  Since it is not a direct line, be prepared to
switch trains en route.  The train takes about 1 hour and 40 minutes
to get to Stony Brook station, which is on-campus.  The Student Union
building is a 5-10 minute walk from the station (a campus map is
available upon request).  Taxis and University shuttle buses are
usually available.  Those going to Danfords Inn should stay on the
train to Port Jefferson -- they will pick you up at the station if
given one week's advance notification.  Trains leave from Penn Station
approximately every 1.5 hours.

Driving Directions:
To get to SUNY Stony Brook by car from New York City (or anywhere
west), take the Long Island Expressway (LIE Route 495) east to exit
62; take Nicolls Road (Route 97) North.  Follow Nicolls Road for about
10 miles.  After about 7 miles you will cross Route 347 (at a major traffic
light); at the third traffic light after this one, turn left into the
main entrance of SUNY Stony Brook.  Follow ``Summer Conference Housing''
signs to Kelly Quad.  Ideally, request a campus map in advance.

To get to Danfords, take Nicolls Road north until it ends at Route 25A
(about 2 miles after the entrance to SUNY), and turn right (east) onto
Route 25A.  Follow Route 25A for 3.5 miles, to a flashing red light
(at Main Street), right in front of the Ferry.  Danfords will be on
the left, just beyond the flashing light.

Those of you traveling from New England might want to consider taking
the Port Jefferson/Bridgeport ferry, which docks right next door to Danfords,
or the Orient Point/New London ferry.
Call for schedules and reservations: Bridgeport (516-473-0286),
Orient Point (516-323-2525).

Weather:
The weather should be pleasant.
The temperatures for Stony Brook in mid-June range from an average high
of 76.6F (24.8C) to an average low of 54.5F (12.5C), with an average
monthly rainfall of 3.25 inches (8.3 cm).
You should bring a light jacket, since Port Jefferson is on the water.

Children and Child Care:
Danfords Inn caters to families, and child care can be arranged.
Contact them for additional information.

