        3rd Annual Video Review of Computational Geometry

Computational geometry concepts are often easiest to
understand visually.  Indeed, most papers in computational geometry
rely on diagrams to communicate the intuition behind their results.
However, static figures are not always adequate to describe geometric
algorithms, since algorithms are inherently dynamic.  This video review
will showcase advances in the use of algorithm animation, visualization,
and interactive computing in the study of computational geometry.

A videotape containing the entire video review program will be distributed
to all registered participants.

Interactive Visualization of Weighted Three-dimensional Alpha Hulls,
        Amitabh Varshney, Frederick P. Brooks, Jr., William V. Wright,
        University of North Carolina

Collision Detection for Interactive Environments,
        Jonathan D. Cohen,  University of North Carolina, Ming C.
        Lin,  Naval Postgraduate School, Dinesh Manocha, and
        Madhav K. Ponamgi, University of North Carolina

Penumbral Shadows,
        Adrian Mariano and Linus Upson,
        The Geometry Center, Minneapolis

Computing the Rectangle Discrepancy,
        David P. Dobkin and Dimitrios Gunopulos, Princeton University

GASP--A System to Facilitate Animating Geometric Algorithms,
        Ayellet Tal and David P. Dobkin, Princeton University

An Animation of a Fixed-Radius All-Nearest Neighbors Algorithm,
        Hans-Peter Lenhof and Michiel Smid,
        Max-Planck-Institut fur Informatik, Saarbrucken

Almost Optimal Polyhedral Separators,
        Herve Bronnimann, Princeton University

An O(n log n) Implementation of the Douglas-Peucker
